<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Block 1 named the reservoirs. Today: how water <em>moves through them</em> in a specific physical basin.</p>
  <p>The unit of analysis for surface water is the <strong>watershed</strong> (drainage basin) — every drop of rain that falls within its boundary ends up in the same outlet stream, river, or coastline. Watersheds nest inside watersheds: the Cooum watershed sits inside the Bay of Bengal catchment; a single neighborhood's stormwater drainage sits inside the Cooum's. The watershed is the right unit because it's the unit politics has to wrestle with: <em>you can't draw a political border across a watershed without making someone upstream or downstream pay</em>. The Cauvery dispute is a watershed politics problem — the basin crosses four states and one union territory.</p>
  <p>Once you have the watershed boundary, you can write a <strong>water budget</strong>. Inputs (precipitation, inflow from upstream, recharge from below) on one side. Outputs (evapotranspiration, withdrawals for irrigation / cities / industry, outflow downstream) on the other. Storage (in lakes, soil moisture, snowpack) in the middle. The balance over a given period — a month, a monsoon, a year — tells you whether the basin is in <strong>deficit</strong> (drawing storage down), <strong>balance</strong> (steady state), or <strong>surplus</strong> (storage rising). Chennai's Cooum and Adyar basins (from U2 Block 3) are typically in deficit through the dry months and briefly in surplus during monsoon peaks. The Cauvery basin as a whole has trended toward annual deficit for the better part of two decades.</p>
  <p>Why this matters for the Position Paper: a Tamil Nadu delta farmer's argument and a Karnataka upstream farmer's argument disagree most sharply on <em>which inputs and outputs count</em> in the basin's budget. Budgets aren't neutral. The framing is part of the argument.</p>
</section>

