<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">🛠️ Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a completed water budget + a 2-sentence claim about deficit/balance/surplus + what would change that classification.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I have calculated a water budget for a small watershed, identified whether it's in deficit, balance, or surplus, and named one factor that would change the classification.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Standard paired water-budget calculation (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Pair work. Using the provided Chennai-area watershed data, compute inputs (precipitation + inflow), storage change, and outputs (evapotranspiration + withdrawals + outflow). Identify whether the watershed is in deficit, balance, or surplus for the month or season given. One budget sheet + one 2-sentence claim per pair.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Cauvery-basin budget connection (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Same calculation as Path A, then apply the framework to the Cauvery basin: which inputs does Karnataka physically control (upstream catchment rainfall, reservoir storage at KRS)? Which outputs does Tamil Nadu measure (delta inflow at the inter-state boundary)? Write a 3-sentence claim about which side of the budget each state cares about most — and why that asymmetry shapes the dispute.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Hydrologist consultation on a budget that doesn't balance (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If your numbers don't balance — and they often won't on the first attempt — open the <a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">Hydrologist</a>. Ask one specific question about which input or output you might be missing or mis-estimating. Document the exchange. This is your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Doc</a> entry for the block.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — deficit vs. balance vs. surplus (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Easy to confuse. A basin can be in deficit for a month (dry season) and surplus for another (monsoon) and roughly in balance over the year. The temporal window matters. Come to the peer-help table with your data; Mr. Ignash will walk through the three classifications with a simple worked example.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

